{"title_page": "Ayisha Davies", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian film producer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=December 2015}}\n'''Ayisha Davies''' is an Australian film producer. She is most famous for producing such films as'' [[Coffin Rock]]'' (2009) and ''The Bloody Sweet Hit'' (2007). Davies has been working within the Australian film industry for eight years and is currently working for Ultra Films. In addition, Davies previously worked in the realm of television, as a production secretary.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nOn 12 July 2017, Davies married Australian actor [[Robert Taylor (Australian actor)|Robert Taylor]]; together, they have a daughter named Scarlet <ref>{{cite news|last=Lee|first=Luaine|title=TV: Robert Taylor goes from Australia to Hollyway by way of weeks in the hospital|url=http://www.pressofatlanticcity.com/life/tv-robert-taylor-goes-from-australia-to-hollyway-by-way/article_8340a248-09f0-5b4c-b794-3108541ea750.html?mode=jqm|accessdate=23 April 2014|newspaper=Press of Atlantic City|date=3 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Career 1999- present ==\n\nDavies began her career in 1999 as a production secretary for Australian television series [[Halifax f.p.]] This early phase in her career was quite short-lived as her time as production secretary lasted only two episodes, which include ''A Murder of Crows'' (15 August 1999) and ''Someone You Know'' (27 June 1999).<ref>{{cite web|title=Ayisha Davies|url=https://pro-labs.imdb.com/name/nm0203596?d=nm_ovrview_contact|publisher=IMDbPro|accessdate=23 April 2014}}</ref>  Davies then went on to become a literary manager where she represented some of the most talented people within the Australian film industry including [[David Lightfoot]] and the filmmakers of SAW.<ref>{{cite web|title=Coffin Rock production notes |url=http://www.bankside-films.com/sites/default/files/coffin_rock_production_notes.pdf |publisher=Bankside Films |accessdate=23 April 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140424020047/http://www.bankside-films.com/sites/default/files/coffin_rock_production_notes.pdf |archivedate=24 April 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref>  In 2007 Davies became the production manager and producer of [[Damian Walshe-Howling]]\u2019s short film The Bloody Sweet Hit  where her career as a producer began to take off, as her film was selected to play at \" The St Kilda International Film Festival, Miami Film Festival, Shorts Film Festival, London's Rushes Soho, [[Flickerfest]], [[Movie Extra]] and most recently sold to [[MTV Italy]].\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Coffin Rock production notes |url=http://www.bankside-films.com/sites/default/files/coffin_rock_production_notes.pdf |publisher=Bankside Films |accessdate=23 April 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140424020047/http://www.bankside-films.com/sites/default/files/coffin_rock_production_notes.pdf |archivedate=24 April 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref>   It was because of husband [[Robert Taylor (Australian actor)|Robert Taylor]] that Davies was introduced to Lightfoot as Taylor had worked with him previously in the 2005 film [[Wolf Creek (film)|Wolf Creek]]. It was because of this introduction that in 2007, Davies then began working alongside Lightfoot at Ultra films.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fenton|first=Andrew|title=Daughter to the Slaughter|url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/news/daughter-to-the-slaughter/story-e6frebt3-1225787591687|accessdate=23 April 2014|newspaper=The Advertiser|date=2009-10-15}}</ref>  Davies first role alongside Lightfoot was as his assistant and 2nd production manager to the film [[Rogue (2007 film)|Rogue]] (2007). Davies was then appointed as a producer for the film [[Coffin Rock]] (2009), co produced short film Press (2010), and worked as a production manager on the film John Doe: Vigilante (2014). In 2014, Davies was working on producing two films,<ref>{{cite web|title=Ayisha Davies|url=https://pro-labs.imdb.com/name/nm0203596?d=nm_ovrview_contact|publisher=IMDbPro|accessdate=23 April 2014}}</ref> the first, [[What Lola Wants]], starring husband [[Robert Taylor (Australian actor)|Robert Taylor]],  and the second, Skylab, a thriller set in outer space. What Lola Wants was released in 2015 and on DVD in April 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/What-Lola-Wants-Robert-Taylor/dp/B01C57Q79S |title=Movies and TV - What Lola Wants |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2017 |website=Amazon.com |publisher=Amazon.com |access-date=4 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Title !! Year !! Production type !! Production role !! Starring\n|-\n| The Bloody Sweet Hit || 2007 || Short film || Production manager and producer || [[Oliver Ackland]], [[Thomas M Wright]] and [[Robert Taylor (Australian actor)|Robert Taylor]]\n|-\n| [[Rogue (2007 film)|Rogue]] || 2007 || Full-length film || Assistant to [[David Lightfoot]] and 2nd production manager || [[Radha Mitchell]], [[Sam Worthington]], [[Stephen Curry (comedian)|Stephen Curry]] and [[Robert Taylor (Australian actor)|Robert Taylor]]\n|-\n| [[Coffin Rock]] || 2009 || Full-length film || Producer, post production supervisor || [[Robert Taylor (Australian actor)|Robert Taylor]], [[Lisa Chappell]] and [[Sam Parsonson]]\n|-\n| Press || 2010 || Short film || Co-producer || Unknown\n|-\n| John Doe: Vigilante || 2014 || Full-length film || Production manager || [[Jamie Bamber]], [[Daniel Lissing]] and Paul O\u2019brien\n|-\n| [[What Lola Wants]] || 2015 || Full-length film || Producer || [[Sophie Lowe]], Beau Knapp and [[Robert Taylor (Australian actor)|Robert Taylor]]\n|-\n| Skylab || To be confirmed || Film in production || Producer || Unknown\n|}\n\n== Television ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Television show !! Episode !! air date !! Network !! Production role !! Starring\n|-\n| [[Halifax f.p.]] || 13: Someone you Know || 27/06/1999 || [[Nine Network]] 